    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3748,
      "reputation" : 831234,
      "user_id" : 5445,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/932fb89b9d4049cec5cba357bf0ae388?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Christian C. Salvad&#243;",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5445/christian-c-salvad%c3%b3"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 145,
    "last_activity_date" : 1633644717,
    "last_edit_date" : 1633644717,
    "creation_date" : 1268982343,
    "answer_id" : 2475528,
    "question_id" : 2018731,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>JavaScript was originally named Mocha, later it was renamed to LiveScript, and then to JavaScript.</p>\n<p>The LiveScript to JavaScript name change came because Netscape and Sun did a license agreement.</p>\n<p>The language was then submitted for standarization to the <a href=\"http://www.ecma-international.org/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">ECMA International</a> Organization. By that time, Netscape didn't allow the use of the &quot;JavaScript&quot; name, so the standarized language is named <a href=\"https://www.ecma-international.org/technical-committees/tc39/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">ECMAScript</a>.</p>\n<p>JavaScript isn't actually an open name. It is currently a <a href=\"https://tsdr.uspto.gov/#caseNumber=75026640&amp;caseType=SERIAL_NO&amp;searchType=statusSearch\" rel=\"noreferrer\">trademark</a> of Oracle (formerly Sun).</p>\n<p>There still a lot of confusion, some people still think that JavaScript, JScript, and ECMAScript are three different languages.</p>\n<p>ECMAScript is the &quot;standards&quot; name for the language.</p>\n<p>JavaScript is technically a &quot;dialect&quot; of ECMAScript, the Mozilla Foundation can use &quot;JavaScript&quot; as the name of their implementations (currently present on the <a href=\"https://github.com/mozilla/rhino\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Rhino</a> and <a href=\"https://spidermonkey.dev\" rel=\"noreferrer\">SpiderMonkey</a> engines).</p>\n<p>In the early days, Microsoft decided also to do what Netscape was doing on their own browser, and they developed <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hbxc2t98%28VS.85%29.aspx\" rel=\"noreferrer\">JScript</a>, which is also an ECMAScript dialect, but was named in this way to avoid trademark issues.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 112686,
      "reputation" : 87,
